To gain unauthorized access to a database, an attacker must not have any authorization or permissions granted by the owner/administrator of the database. The attacker must have either:

1. Knowledge about how the database is designed and implemented;
2. Have knowledge about who has access to the database or what specific privileges are associated with a particular user account; or
3. Have gained unauthorized access to the system using another method such as brute force attacks, social engineering tactics or insider threats.

In many cases, an attacker will need to gain unauthorized access by attempting to breach one of these points in the above scenario. Some common methods include:

1. Phishing - sending a fake email or link to the target user that leads them to the database login page;
2. Man-in-the-middle attacks (MITM) - intercepting and tampering with data between the attacker and the server;
3. Brute force attacks - using automated tools to try all possible passwords or usernames until one succeeds in gaining access.

However, no method is 100% foolproof when it comes to database security. Attackers can also use insider threats such as stealing credentials or access tokens from employees or third-party services like AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) or Google Cloud Identity & Access Management (GCIA).

